   "source": [
    "## Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "How does the distribution of birth months of the 2022 and 2026 US Winter Olympic athletes differ from the general American population, based off of the 2000 census?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Every four years, many athletes of snow and ice sports such as figure skating, skiing, and curling participate in a major international multi-sport event known as the Winter Olympics. The competitors who reach this stage are considered elite athletes, representing the highest level of performance in their respective sports. However, the development of elite athletes may be influenced by external factors before they reach the Olympic stage. One such factor is the relative age effect (RAE), which suggests that athletes born earlier in the calendar year may have performance advantages in age-restricted sports leagues <a name=\"cite_ref-3\"></a>[<sup>3</sup>](#cite_note-3). Because these athletes are often slightly older than their peers, they may be more physically and emotionally mature and thus more likely selected during early selection processes for those sports. Overtime, this advantage can contribute to them being more advanced athletes.\n",
    "\n",
    "The first study to show the relative age effect was Barnsley, Thompson, and Barnsley in 1985. They looked at top junior and pro hockey leagues in Canada. They found that way more players were born in January, February, and March than in October, November, and December.<a name=\"cite_ref-1\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-1)\n",
    "\n",
    "Many later studies looked for the same pattern in other sports. In 2009, Cobley and his team did a review that combined 38 studies across 14 sports and 16 countries. They found that for every 2 elite athletes born in the last three months of the year, there were about 3 born in the first three months. The effect was small but showed up almost everywhere.<a name=\"cite_ref-2\"></a>[<sup>2</sup>](#cite_note-2) A 2020 study by Joyner and his team checked Olympic medal winners from 2000 to 2018 and found the RAE shows up even at the top level. Athletes born in spring were more likely to win gold than athletes born in winter (Q4).<a name=\"cite_ref-3\"></a>[<sup>3</sup>](#cite_note-3) Raschner and his team in 2012 looked at the first Winter Youth Olympic Games. They found a strong RAE in skiing, snowboarding, and Nordic combined, but almost none in figure skating, which suggests the effect depends a lot on the sport.<a name=\"cite_ref-4\"></a>[<sup>4</sup>](#cite_note-4)\n",
    "\n",
    "**References**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. <a name=\"cite_note-1\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-1) Barnsley, R. H., Thompson, A. H., & Barnsley, P. E. (1985). Hockey success and birthdate: The relative age effect. *Canadian Association for Health, Physical Education, and Recreation Journal*, 51, 23–28. https://www.researchgate.net/publication/284328248_Hockey_success_and_birthdate_The_relative_age_effect\n",
    "2. <a name=\"cite_note-2\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-2) Cobley, S., Baker, J., Wattie, N., & McKenna, J. (2009). Annual age-grouping and athlete development: A meta-analytical review of relative age effects in sport. *Sports Medicine*, 39(3), 235–256. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19290678/\n",
    "3. <a name=\"cite_note-3\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-3) Joyner, P. W., Lewis, J. S., Dawood, R. S., Mallon, W. J., Kirkendall, D. T., & Garrett, W. E. (2020). Relative Age Effect: Beyond the Youth Phenomenon. *American Journal of Lifestyle Medicine*, 14(5). https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7692010/\n",
    "4. <a name=\"cite_note-4\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-4) Raschner, C., Müller, L., & Hildebrandt, C. (2012). The role of a relative age effect in the first winter Youth Olympic Games in 2012. *British Journal of Sports Medicine*, 46(15), 1038–1043. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22976907/\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Hypothesis\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We hypothesize that there will be there will be a higher proportion of US Winter Olympic athletes from the 2022 and 2026 Winters Olympics born in the earlier calender months (January to March) compared to the average US population. This is because in all of the prior works that we researched, the relative age effect applied for most prior Winter Olympic athletes. As such, we expect for this to be applied to recent Winter Olympic athletes as well."
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To answer our research question, our ideal datasets would include the birthday months of all 2022 and 2026 US Winter Olympic athletes and all individuals born in the US in 2000. In terms of number of observations required, we would ideally have around 4 million observations for births in 2000, which was the number of births in the US in 2000 [1]. We also want 224 and 232 observations for US Winter Olympics athletes in 2022 and 2026 respectively, which was the number of competing US Winter Olympic athletes in 2022 [2] and 2026 [3]. In a perfect world, this data will be collected by governmental agencies, who could collect them through birth certificates, Olympics organizers, who could collect them from athlete registrations, or healthcare organizations, who could collect them from insurance data. All of these organizations will collect the number of people born in each month in a year and store them in CSV files or websites (which may require scraping).\n",
    "\n",
    "After some research, we found two datasets that best match the ideal, though with some limitations. \n",
    "\n",
    "The dataset for the birth months of the general US population comes from FiveThirtyEight, which used to be a national polling organization, at https://github.com/fivethirtyeight/data/blob/master/births/US_births_2000-2014_SSA.csv as a CSV file. This dataset contains the year month, date of month, day of week, and the count of births from 2000 to 2014. For our analysis, the most important variables that we would use would be the month and count of births for the year 2000. \n",
    "\n",
    "The second dataset for the birth months of US Winter Olympics Athletes comes from https://www.olympedia.org/, which is a website containing data on Olympic athletes compiled by Olympic historians. This dataset contains data such as athletes’ names, date of birth, Olympics team affiliation, games they competed in, sport and place of birth. For our analysis, in addition to only looking at US athletes competing in Winter Olympics 2022 and 2024, the most important variables we would use is birth month and the number of athletes born in each month.\n",
    "\n",
    "Looking at the two datasets, we realize there are some differences between our ideal datasets and our real datasets. Our real general US population dataset comes from 2000 with approximately the same number of ideal observations. However, this real dataset is limited in its origin, which is through a non-governmental source, which may limit its reliability. Ultimately, through analysis, we hope to establish a relationship between birth month and presence in the Olympics, and find any patterns when the two distributions are compared. \n",
    "\n",
    "SOURCES: \n",
    "* [https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nvsr/nvsr50/nvsr50_05.pdf](https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nvsr/nvsr50/nvsr50_05.pdf)\n",
    "* [https://www.teamusa.com/beijing-2022-olympic-games/meet-team-usa/athletes](https://www.teamusa.com/beijing-2022-olympic-games/meet-team-usa/athletes)\n",
    "* [https://www.teamusa.com/milano-cortina-2026/olympics/roster](https://www.teamusa.com/milano-cortina-2026/olympics/roster)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
